The best approach is to adopt the **`System.IO.Abstractions`** NuGet package — it's the battle-tested standard for wrapping file system statics.

### 1. Install the packages

```bash
dotnet add <YourProject> package System.IO.Abstractions
dotnet add <YourTestProject> package System.IO.Abstractions.TestingHelpers
```

### 2. Register in DI

```csharp
builder.Services.AddSingleton<IFileSystem, FileSystem>();
```

### 3. Inject `IFileSystem` into your classes

```csharp
public class ConfigManager(IFileSystem fileSystem)
{
    public string Load(string path)
        => fileSystem.File.ReadAllText(path);

    public void Save(string path, string content)
        => fileSystem.File.WriteAllText(path, content);

    public bool OutputDirExists(string path)
        => fileSystem.Directory.Exists(path);
}
```

### 4. Test with `MockFileSystem`

```csharp
var mockFs = new MockFileSystem(new Dictionary<string, MockFileData>
{
    { "/config.json", new MockFileData("{\"key\": \"value\"}") }
});
mockFs.AddDirectory("/output");

var manager = new ConfigManager(mockFs);

Assert.Equal("{\"key\": \"value\"}", manager.Load("/config.json"));
Assert.True(manager.OutputDirExists("/output"));

manager.Save("/new.txt", "hello");
Assert.Equal("hello", mockFs.File.ReadAllText("/new.txt"));
```

**Why this over a custom wrapper?** `System.IO.Abstractions` covers the entire `System.IO` surface — `File`, `Directory`, `Path`, `FileInfo`, etc. — so you won't need to expand a custom interface every time you use a new method. The `MockFileSystem` gives you an in-memory filesystem out of the box with no mocking framework needed.

Once the package is in place, you can use the **migrate-static-to-wrapper** skill to bulk-replace existing `File.*` / `Directory.*` call sites across your project. Just say the word!
